node.text:
Did you know Yellowstone removes hazard trees from campgrounds and picnic areas? Like all living things, trees have a life cycle and eventually die.  Employees like Brian reduce the risk of personal injury or property damage by identifying the trees with the highest potential for failure and removing them before they cause problems. Salvaged wood is used for various projects throughout the park.

“During a wind storm a few years ago, we had a live tree fall on a campground host’s RV. Thankfully, everyone was OK, but the RV was totaled. It was a great reminder of the importance of this work to keep people safe.” –Brian Teets, Resource Management Coordinator #WhatWeDoWednesdays

node.title: Minute Out In It - Hazard Tree Crew

node.text:
Yellowstone Volcano Observatory Scientist-in-Charge Mike Poland provides an update on activity in Yellowstone during the month of June 2021 from the boardwalk near Echinus Geyser (the largest acid geyser in the world!).

The Yellowstone Seismic Network located 445 earthquakes in the Yellowstone National Park region. Subsidence of Yellowstone Caldera, which has been ongoing since 2015, slowed during May/June 2021 reflecting seasonal groundwater recharge. And for the first time since April 2018, Steamboat Geyser did not have any water eruptions during a calendar month. Overall, the time between eruptions has been lengthening, which may be an indication that the current cycle of activity at the geyser is coming to a close. Dr. Poland walks you through the publicly-available data and explains recent events.

Thank you to our colleagues at @usgsvolcanoes for the latest monthly update!

node.title: Yellowstone Volcano Observatory Monthly Update - July 1, 2021

node.text:
News Release: If you plan to travel to Yellowstone National Park this summer, plan ahead and recreate responsibly to protect yourself and this wild and awe-inspiring place.

Summer is Yellowstone’s most popular season. Expect long lines at entrance stations, extremely busy facilities and destinations, as well as delayed travel times due to heavy traffic and wildlife jams. If you want a less-crowded experience, arrive early or stay late and avoid main attractions such as Old Faithful, Grand Prismatic Spring, the Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone and Norris Geyser Basin during peak hours.

To learn more about tips for planning a park visit this summer and how to #RecreateResponsibly, visit the link in our bio!

node.title: Visiting Yellowstone this summer? Plan ahead and recreate responsibly!

It's May, the snow is melting, and the roads are mostly open, so it's time for geologists, geophysicists, and geochemists to head into Yellowstone to start projects they have been planning for the last several months. Mike Poland, the scientist-in-charge of the Yellowstone Volcano Observatory, talks about future field plans and recent activity at Yellowstone.

Thanks to our colleagues at @@usgsvolcanoes for the latest monthly update!

node.text:
There are thousands of volcanic features distributed throughout the southwest United States, which are grouped together in volcanic fields. The Yellowstone Volcano Observatory (YVO) monitors these volcanoes using a combination of techniques. While YVO hasn’t seen anything to suggest magma is on the move, the area is stretched and pulled apart to produce numerous tectonic earthquakes. YVO keeps an eye on these volcanoes and the Yellowstone Volcano, as described in this monthly video update by Mike Poland, YVO scientist-in-charge.

Thanks to our friends at @usgsvolcanoes for the latest monthly update!

For closed captions and to read the full transcript, visit the link in our bio.

Have you ever wondered how we get park roads snow-free for your spring visit?

Beginning this past Monday evening, all oversnow travel via snowmobile/snowcoach ended to allow for our crews to begin clearing a winter's worth of snow. Although most park roads will be closed for the next few weeks, the road between the North and Northeast entrances remains open to personal vehicles year-round, weather-permitting.

Be sure to check the status of roads before venturing into the park by signing up to receive Yellowstone road alerts on your mobile phone by texting "82190" to 888-777, calling 307-344-2117 to listen to a recorded message, or checking our park roads page on our website: nps.gov/yell.

To watch this video with closed captions, visit the link in our bio.

News Release: On Saturday, March 13, a pilot supporting park wildlife studies saw the first grizzly bear of 2021. From the air, the pilot watched the bear interact with wolves at a carcass in the northern part of the park. This is the first sighting of a grizzly bear in the park this year, although tracks have been seen on several occasions in the last two weeks.

The first bear sighting of 2020 occurred on March 7.

To learn more about bear safety and read the full news release, visit: go.nps.gov/21005 (link in our bio).

Video description: A grizzly bear meanders down trails and digs in meadows searching for food after emerging from hibernation.

News Release from the U.S. Department of Justice District of Wyoming: Unauthorized Yellowstone park guide sentenced for illegal activities.

Acting United States Attorney Bob Murray announced today that Theodore Eugene Garland, age 60 of Edmond, Oklahoma, was sentenced on seven counts of illegal activities and violations in Yellowstone National Park. Garland appeared in front of Magistrate Judge Mark L. Carman in Mammoth Hot Springs, Yellowstone National Park, Wyoming, on July 2, 2021, for the sentencing.

Theodore Garland has a social media page, a podcast, and a guidebook. All three have overlapping pictures and posts about his guided tours in Yellowstone, which violated closures and other park regulations and encouraged visitors to do the same. Some of the examples included providing unauthorized guided tours; trespassing on thermal grounds; violating swimming closures and cliff jumping; creating “hot pots in rivers;” and disturbing wildlife.

Judge Carman sentenced Garland on the seven counts, resulting in a seven-day jail sentence; a total of $600 in fines and fees; a one-time payment of $500 to Yellowstone Forever Geological Resource Fund; and a ban from Yellowstone National Park until December 31, 2021. He was also ordered to write an introduction/forward to his guidebook communicating respect for the park and removing references of illegal activity by July 16, 2021. Garland will serve five years of unsupervised probation and shall “not promote violations of laws in the national parks in any way.”

To read the full news release, visit: go.nps.gov/210719 (link in bio).

Trip Day takes on this geologic gem!

Trip Day Thursday
Lake Village to Canyon Village
 
A trip to Yellowstone is hardly complete without seeing this awe-inspiring natural wonder. Since the Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone is so incredible in scope, here are a few facts below to help you plan your visit to the Canyon area:
-The many different colors in the canyon are caused by an oxidation of iron compounds in the rhyolite rock, which has been hydrothermally altered. The colors indicate the presence or absence of water in the individual iron compounds and hydration of minerals in the rock; most of the yellows in the canyon result from iron and sulfur in the rock. In simpler terms, you could say that the canyon is “rusting.”
-The 308-foot Lower Falls has an iconic green stripe in it. A notch in the lip of the brink makes the water deeper and keeps it from mixing with air, so it appears darker as it goes over the edge.
-There are a variety of beautiful overlooks along the North Rim and South Rim drives. Some are steep and require a trek down into the canyon (for example, the Brink of the Lower Falls trail) and some are accessed via short, paved sidewalks (such as Artist Point). Check the park website linked in our bio to determine which overlooks best fit your needs!

Before we go on to the Norris Geyser Basin, let us know which facts, thermal features, historical sites, scenic views, and other natural features you’d like to know more about.

News Release: The park hosted 938,845 recreation visits in June 2021, making it the park’s most-visited June on record. This is a 64% increase from June 2020 (573,205 recreational visits) and a 20% increase from June 2019 (781,853 recreation visits).

So far in 2021, the park has hosted 1,587,998 recreation visits, up 17% from 2019. This year is compared to 2019 instead of 2020 because of COVID-19.

Summer is Yellowstone’s busiest season. Millions of people visit the park in June, July and August. If you plan to travel to Yellowstone this summer, plan ahead, expect crowding, recreate responsibly and take the Yellowstone Pledge to protect yourself and the park.

To learn more about how these numbers are calculated and to read the full news release, visit: go.nps.gov/21020 (link in bio).

Did you know Yellowstone removes hazard trees from campgrounds and picnic areas? Like all living things, trees have a life cycle and eventually die.  Employees like Brian reduce the risk of personal injury or property damage by identifying the trees with the highest potential for failure and removing them before they cause problems. Salvaged wood is used for various projects throughout the park.

“During a wind storm a few years ago, we had a live tree fall on a campground host’s RV. Thankfully, everyone was OK, but the RV was totaled. It was a great reminder of the importance of this work to keep people safe.” –Brian Teets, Resource Management Coordinator #WhatWeDoWednesdays

Heads Up! Smoky conditions are expected to continue this week in the park.

Wind can blow smoke from far-away wildland fires for hundreds of miles, which is what's causing the current smoky conditions in the park. As record-breaking heat and historic drought conditions continue in the western U.S. this summer, be sure to check air quality conditions before spending a lot of time outdoors!

To view an interactive map showing where smoke is coming from, visit: fire.airnow.gov (link in bio).

Photos: (1) Smoky conditions at Roosevelt Arch on July 12, 2021; (2) Roosevelt Arch on a typical summer day.

Yellowstone Volcano Observatory Scientist-in-Charge Mike Poland provides an update on activity in Yellowstone during the month of June 2021 from the boardwalk near Echinus Geyser (the largest acid geyser in the world!).

The Yellowstone Seismic Network located 445 earthquakes in the Yellowstone National Park region. Subsidence of Yellowstone Caldera, which has been ongoing since 2015, slowed during May/June 2021 reflecting seasonal groundwater recharge. And for the first time since April 2018, Steamboat Geyser did not have any water eruptions during a calendar month. Overall, the time between eruptions has been lengthening, which may be an indication that the current cycle of activity at the geyser is coming to a close. Dr. Poland walks you through the publicly-available data and explains recent events.

Thank you to our colleagues at @usgsvolcanoes for the latest monthly update!

News Release: Parkwide vehicle entries through the Fourth of July weekend showed an 8% increase over the same weekend in 2019. This year is compared to 2019 instead of 2020 because of COVID-19.

Summer is Yellowstone’s busiest season. Millions of people visit the park in June, July and August. If you plan to travel to Yellowstone this summer, plan ahead, expect crowding and recreate responsibly to protect yourself and the park.

To view visitation statistics from the weekend and learn more about how these stats are calculated, visit: go.nps.gov/21019 (link in bio).

Woahhh we’re halfway there on our weekly Trip Days around Yellowstone National Park! Six segments down, six more to go. 

Trip Day Thursday
Lake Village to East Entrance
 
Yellowstone Lake is scenic central within the park; there are many picturesque areas to take in from the lakeside or from higher elevations. If you love challenging hikes with incredible panoramas, look no further than Avalanche Peak. This steep and difficult hike (a 4.7 mile/7.6 km round-trip) offers rewarding vistas at the top. For those who don’t love heights, the shoreline along Yellowstone Lake is known for its sweeping mountain views and great fly fishing spots. If trails or walks along the beach aren’t your thing, the roadside scenery is also amazing. Fishing Bridge offers incredible views of Mt. Sheridan, and you can even see the distant Tetons from the road towards the East Entrance! 

Before we turn back towards Canyon Village, let us know which facts, thermal features, historical sites, scenic views, and other natural features you’d like to know more about.

Did you know the @nationalparkservice is the only U.S land management agency with an Office of Public Health? This year, Yellowstone commemorates the 100-year anniversary of the partnership with the U.S. Public Health Service and NPS. Commissioned officers like George provide services that include surveying drinking water and wastewater systems, inspecting food vendors, and responding to and preventing illness outbreaks.

“In addition to being an incredible natural and cultural resource, parks are also a powerful resource to promote human health. Our partnership mitigates the risk of people getting sick while they visit, so they can focus on getting out and exploring the wonders of Yellowstone." –Commander George Larsen, Public Health Consultant #WhatWeDoWednesdays

Learn more about the partnership by visiting the link in our bio.

node.text:
Tip Tuesday:  Enjoy the beauty of the colorful microorganisms within the geothermal systems of Yellowstone, but please do not touch.
Yellowstone National Park was established in 1872 primarily to protect geothermal areas that contain about half the world’s active geysers. Because these geothermal areas have been protected, we’ve learned a lot about them and the thermophiles (heat loving organisms) that thrive within their hot water systems.
Just a few of the things that we have learned over the years about thermophiles -
Thermophiles called cyanobacteria were responsible for the oxygenation of our atmosphere. They were the first photosynthesizers converting light energy into oxygen. Without bacteria, in particular, cyanobacteria, humans would not be here.
Another thermophile, called thermus aquaticus, lives in extremely hot water. An enzyme isolated from this thermophile is used to amplify specific DNA sequences and is used to make medical diagnoses and treatments where genetic information is key to improving health. 
The thermophilic communities are also studied by scientists searching for evidence of life on other planets, the connection is, extreme environments.
It is unsafe and unlawful to walk in thermal runoff and to touch or change it in anyway. The ground is fragile, there can be hot water surges, and it ruins the colorful beauty for everyone else. So please stay on boardwalks, enjoy the colors and take photos, but do not touch.
